# Security Rules

## Secrets
- Never hardcode API keys or secrets
- All secrets in .env.local (gitignored)
- .env.example must list every required variable with a placeholder
- Never log environment variables — not even to confirm they loaded

## PII Handling
User CVs, personal details, and questionnaire answers are PII.
- Never log extracted CV text or personal details
- Never include raw PII in error messages returned to client
- Supabase Storage paths scoped to userId — no cross-user access
- RLS (Row Level Security) enabled and tested on every table

## Row Level Security — Required Policies

For every table:
  -- Users can only read/write their own rows
  CREATE POLICY "user_owns_row" ON table_name
    FOR ALL USING (auth.uid() = user_id);

Never bypass RLS with the service_role key in client-side code.
Service role key: server only, never exposed to browser.

## Prompt Injection Defense
User-uploaded documents may contain adversarial text.
Before injecting any user content into a prompt:
  1. Strip known injection patterns: "ignore previous", "new instruction", "system:", "###"
  2. Limit chunk length — never inject > 2000 tokens from a single chunk
  3. Wrap user content in XML tags (Claude treats inner content as data, not instruction)

## Auth Verification
Every API route must verify auth — see backend-api.mdc.
Middleware must protect all /dashboard routes.

```typescript
// src/middleware.ts
export async function middleware(request: NextRequest) {
  const supabase = createMiddlewareClient({ req: request, res })
  const { data: { session } } = await supabase.auth.getSession()
  if (!session && request.nextUrl.pathname.startsWith('/dashboard')) {
    return NextResponse.redirect(new URL('/sign-in', request.url))
  }
}
```

## Rate Limiting
Use Upstash Redis for distributed rate limiting.
Apply to: /api/generate, /api/apply, /api/documents (10/day each)
Never rely on client-side throttling alone.

## Interview-Ready Security Explanation
"CVs contain PII — I apply GDPR-style principles: storage encrypted at rest
via Supabase, access scoped via RLS so users can only read their own data,
service_role key never exposed to the browser, and prompt injection mitigated
by sanitizing and XML-wrapping all user content before it enters any LLM call."
